ap. I remember the last time - I think that he ever he hit - he - well he didn't hit him, but you see, Hal would take notice of what other children told him. Instead of asking his own children what had happened - these'll come up, Mr Mellor, your boy did 
s
o and so, you know, knocked me down and that. Well then he would whip - without speaking - come home and attack them. See, well he - one day Leslie came run - running and now I shall never forget it, because it seemed - I thought my good gracious, Mr Pres
t
on always says I'm psychic, because of what I tell him, he said, well Mrs Mellor, he read one of my poems, he said, you must be psychic, well anyway - he came running in one day and he said, out the way mummy, out the way, he said, there's somebody'll be 
c
arrying flowers and it won't be me. Now that wasn't a strange thing, he wasn't more than about eight years of age. He'd be between eight and nine I know he was quite - well he was no big boy, and he ran upstairs, and I stood at the bottom of the stairs an
d
 held the rails, and my husband came in running, white with passion, he said, out of the way, Kitty. I said, no. And he put out his hand to touch my hand, I said - and I said. Hal, if you touch my hand - I said, I'll kill you, if it's the last thing I do.
 
You're not touching that child. He was quite as death. I said you're not touching him while you're in that temper. You do not know what has happened, and he's not going to be punished. Well I shall never forget his expression. A funny thing for a child to
 say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What had the boy done?
