Well - the - the - the solicitor that was conducting Auntie Beat's - business for her - died. And in between - her partner - had collected some more lawyers together and they
 made a - what you call - something like a combined will. They made up one. So that then - yes. They made up one see that he I suppose each - each claiming so much of the property. So instead of having it for nothing she paid - eight hundred and seventy-f
ive pounds for it I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was in a later period when Auntie Beat took it over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
That's right, after my mother - yes, after - after mother died. No, after - after - after grandpa Laleg died I suppose because mother had bought it, it must h
ave - and then my father - mother bought it you see. Well let's see. Now it must have been on a life that my mother bought it. See, and - I don't know what - mother had it very cheap because I told you all the farmers were they would - wouldn't bid agains
t her, but there was one lease. And - when this lease died - of course - they claimed you see and - Auntie Beat took it over, bought it.
