\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I want to ask how you and your husband m
anaged the housekeeping in those years before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
I had my housekeeping money. And he paid for the rent - and rates, but I had my housekeeping money, for which I was very glad because if he gave me all his money - with four children I could have sp
ent it. I could have done. If you've a family of four you see to educate and feed and all - costs a lot of money. Now I remember - during the years of depression, that was between the two world warsz, my husband's wages in the dockyard - went to below thr
ee pound a week. Now I had - he had to pay the rate and the rent and the rates and I brought up my family for three - several years, all the time the depression was on - on thirty-eight and sixpence a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you in those years the early years discu
ss with your husband how the money he allowed you was to be spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh no, he gave me of course that was - that my - free - you know, I had my housekeeping money and I could spend it as I liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you always know what actually Mr Mellor earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
I couldn't - no, I never knew his - I never bothered. I never bothered as long as I had my housekeeping money - I knew he was saving every ha'penny, you see - I knew that, he - he didn't drink or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In the years from the time you came ho
me from Russia until you went to Devenport you were traveling about and you made this your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This was our home, between - yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 All your married life from then on was spent in Plymouth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What was the first house o
f your own that you had in Plymouth, what was the address was it, what sort of house was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 It was a new house - in Bute Road, fourteen Bute Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When did you move into that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well let - I think about 1936. I think. We were in a ren
ted home for twenty-one years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
When you first moved to Devonport you went into lodgings, how long was that, how long before you had your own home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh - several months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. Because in between, I came home - and had my third so
n. See, and then when we went - back - I went to live with my - brother and his wife, for - to - look - for a home, you see, and it wasn't - we weren't there very long before Hal came home one morning, from night work, and he said, I've got good news for 
y
ou Kitty, he said, I've found a house. Well I then immediately sent down to - mother - to get someone to - see if she could send someone up to help me, and there was a young cousin into Truro - she was about eighteen and - Rene came up - and stayed at Nel
l
's for a couple of nights you know and - until the furniture arrived from - Southampton. And then we went up I remember that the men - they did put the - lino in the dining room, and put all the dining room furniture in, and they did put up two beds, but 
that's all they did, but when my husband came home he was surprised to find a lovely fire in the gate and - and a lovely hot meal waiting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This was 14 Bute Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That - no, that was number three Bute Road. That was the rented home.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Can you recall how long did you live in number three Bute Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Twenty-one years darling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Can you remember how many rooms there were in the house at number three?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, six rooms and a - scullery. Six - real rooms you know, and a scullery. With an outdoor convenience. There was no bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 So that comprised what downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Comprised a - well wheat - what I call my sitting room, dining room, kitchen and - and scullery. And three large bedrooms upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Were there any relatives or lodgers living with you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
You said that your furniture arrived from Southampton, had you had a residence in Southampton before that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, we lived in - Southampton - well not very long. But we lived in Southampton - 
in Totton Road, 14 Fishers Road, I can remember it now, Totton. He was working for - an engineering firm at Totton. I believe it was Lord Buleigh, I don't know, but he was the chief engineer there at some works. I was never concerned about - anything - yo
u know, as long as I had my housekeeping money, I just managed -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you remember what period that was when you were in Southampton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
We were in Southampton - for a period of what - oh I shouldn't say more than six months. Before war broke out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Just before you went down to Devonport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. Becore war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And prior to that you made your home here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. At - at intervals, whenever you know, when - ever we were going about. But you see we lived for twenty-one years in - in 21, in number 21.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And twenty-one years in number 3?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Twenty - it's twenty-one years in number three, well right opposite us there was a large piece of ground. There are six houses built on it now so you can tell the size. And - a police sergeant 
- had a - cultivated this ground into a large garden. Well he gave it up, and he came to our neighbour and asked a Mr Peters if he would like to take it over. So he said yes. So we were great friends, Mrs Peters and I, and - they came down to us and asked
 us if we would share this large field with them which we did for a while, and then we took over the whole lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever have paid help in the house when you lived at Bute Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, I had to. I was told by doctor I was - I was not allowed
 to stoop or kneel. In fact -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was this help living in or daily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, no, came in the mornings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Just one person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What sort of duties had she then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh she had to do all the floors. All the heavy stuff. Now - during all th
e years of my married life, I baked my - all my own bread and cakes, my children never knew the taste of bought stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you make your own jams and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
I made all of my own jams and jellies. And every - is this being recorded? And every sp
ring - Ada and I used to go out with a large basket, and a trowel. And there was the place right opposite of us called Compton Path Fields, and we used to go our through and I used to pick - dandelions - stinging nettles what's the one that's called here 
-
 stinging nettle, the one that was here on the - grows here on the hedge, well every - every herb - that I could find, and make herb beer. Now my children - were free of any ills, I - for seventeen years I did not have a doctor in for my children. Only on
e exception, that was when Leslie had diphtheria. I always had something in you know to cure them. And - but every spring - I was a regular thing for me to make herb beer, and I know that - I - we had friends and one special }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 friend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  the first thing when he u
sed to come in the spring they used to come out to visit us - and stay to tea you know, and his first question was before he got in the house nearly, any herby beer Kitty?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You drank it as a beverage but also as a medicine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes. Oh yes. And t
hen I used to come home - in the - in the holidays - or during times, and pick all the elder I could. And I used to take that and dry it. And put it in bags. And if any of the children had a cold. I would take a handful of elder, put it in a saucepan, ste
e
p it - then strain it, and sweeten it with honey. Now that cured all my - the - their chest colds and anything, always went to the elderberry and I made elderberry wine, and blackberry wine. Oh I was always busy, I never knew what - I never knew - my hand
s were working always. I made all my own clothes, all my daughter's clothes up until the day she went to Canada.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This paid help that you had, that was Ada was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No, she was called - oh - oh - now it's just - just the name. Well anyway, I rememb
er her - she stayed with me for - she was with me for years, and she was with us - when the war broke out, the second world war. And - she came the Saturday morning - and when she went away Hal was out in the garden sitting on a chair you know, it was sun
s
hine. And she said - cheerio Mr Mellor, see you again on Monday if old Hitler doesn't get me. And it's a funny thing, on Sunday night - Hitler dropped a bomb - on their home a three storeyed house it was, let out in three flats, and it was demolished comp
l
etely. And the only thing - that was left out of that house, pianos everything went, the only thing that was found - was the leg of one chair, and one hand with a ring on it. And - my - Ronald then, you see, used to go around and visit every house that wa
s bombed, that was one part of his duties, see he went in the Army but he was no sooner there than the council sent for him to come back, he was so - useful you know, he knew the city so well, and then he used to go visit -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In your early married life y
ou had paid help then, this lady was cleaning the house and so on, did she ever look after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh no, they were grown up then you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I mean in your early married life when the children were small?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, no, I - no, I - oh yes, 
I did because I had my young cousin over to-stay with me so long, you see, I had spent many months in bed with flebitis, I had about ten bouts - or more of flebitis, it was nothing new you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Before 1918 do you remember if you employed anyone to do 
domestic work in the house apart from your cousin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No, I always had a relative to come up when I was ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was the washing done at home in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes, I did all of my own washing - and ironing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And made all the clothes for yourself and your daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, I knit all my childrens socks, vests, everything when they were tiny. All their little pants, but of course when they got bigger I - I - you know, that got past me, I used to buy them, but until -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Where did you buy their clothes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Pardon? Oh generally at the Co-op, I - I was a regular Co-operator you know, I believed in doing things, you know, really well and - I - I joined the Co-operative and I had all that I could there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Would that include shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. Mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was there any special time for buying clothes or shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well during the January sales. I used - do you know - I used to go in town every January, the January sales, and buy my Christmas presents for the next year. Now I bought t
oys - that would have cost me perhaps a pound, but in the January sales I could have 'em for a shilling or a couple of shilling. So that I used to go every January, that - I used to tour the town of Plymouth all - walk about and see the - for all of my - 
next years Christmas presents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
In the home in the early days, during the first world war and before did Mr Mellor do any jobs in the home like decorating or repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Nothing. I did all the decorating. Painting and papering, I've papered and painted that house right through, and when the landlord came to see it he wouldn't believe it. He said, you had a craftsman in to do this Mr Mellor. I said, no, I didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you see much of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. Scarcely ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was he a good landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, they wonderful, they - they just left me - you know, I - they came for the rent and - that's all, but - I know that - he passed this remark, he wanted - to see through the house to see - how it was looking you know. And he wouldn't belie
ve that I done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did your husband help with sort of tell the children stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, he would do that and - you know, we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Would he take them out sometimes without you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, I don't think he ever took them out without me. We - no, 
we were never parted. My husband wanted no one but me. I sometimes wish he had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 If you went out you went together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes, everywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did he read aloud to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. When they were tiny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did he help with any undressing or dressing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Were there any regular household tasks for the children to do to help you when they were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes. Now I shall never forget it as long as I live. Every Sunday they used to go to Sunday school in the mornings you know, 
and then into chapel, they went to Sunday school - again in the afternoons, and - Monday mornings my first job - after I done the beds and things was to clean all the Sunday shoes, because we had best shoes - second shoes, that was for schools, and old sh
o
es to put on when they came home. When they come home from school - off came their school clothes, and old clothes were put on, you see I had to be very careful because - money was low then. So I took care of everything that I did, but - and I remember on
e
 morning, I was cleaning the shoes, and my little Owen was only two and a half, and he said, me cean soos mummy, and I said, no you can't darling. And he stamped his little feet, you know, and he said, me keen soos I say mummy. And I said, you can't darli
n
g. But he still on and insisted on his shouting so I said, all right my son, come along, so mother took off her apron and - got on my hat and coat, went into Woolworths, bought two little brushes, one a little hard scrubbing brush, and the other one about
 the same size and a little smooth one. And I came home - and took his shoes on my hand, and showed him how to clean them. Now from that day forward - I've never cleaned any shoes belonging to that child. And he was only two and a half.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the children do any other tasks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
They had to - oh yes. Oh yes, you see, at first when we went there we - we didn't know anyone, didn't know about help or anything, so I had to depend on my children. Well they washed all the dishes. They polished the floors. Th
ey brought in the coal. You see they did - and - there's this about it, when a meal was over, I never had to say to my children, now come on, hurry up and clear the dishes, they took it as a matter of course you know, see, they took it between them, there
 was - say Phil and Ron would wash one week and Leslie and Owen the other or else, you know, they would share it between them. But - I never knew what it was to wash a dish. After they came home from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What time did you get them off to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh about eight o'clock. That's when they were younger you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you put them to bed or did they go with themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh I always put them. Always put them you know but I always stayed with them and saw them - had - heard them say their prayers you know. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever have family prayers with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well not really family prayers but we - every - you know, we were both in - Mutley Wesleayan choir for many years, and - after we came home - on Sunday nights - we used to go i
nto the sitting room and pick out our favourite hymns this is especially in the winter you know, and - I have a good sing-song. Well we - we did it always, but especially during the winter, and one day when I was going up the road the lady stopped me and 
s
he said you're Mrs Mellor aren't you? I said, yes. She said, oh you give us such pleasure. I said, why? She said, well we go out in the - Path Fields, that was right opposite our house, she said, and listen to you and your family singing. And she said, it
'
s beautiful. She said, we got - we are Church of England and they went to St Augustines church which was down below, and they came up and then afterwards they used to go out and she said they used to listen regularly to her - to our singing. 'Cos my husba
nd had a wonderful baritone voice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the children share the bed or bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well had the three large bedrooms. We slept in one. Philippa slept in the other and in the other bedroom we had two beds. And the two little boys slept together and - Ronald had a single bed to himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What room did you use for bathing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
We lived the - we used the kitchen then, there was no bathroom in the first house. At all. So then I had a large sinc bath, you know, very large one. And the bath used to be brought in front of the kitchen fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When would they have their bathing night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Saturday evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh as - well there was - never any shortage of clean clothes because - I did all my own washing. And when my childre
n got old enough you know - in their room there was a chest of drawers. Well each boy - had his own - drawer. See, Ronald would have his shirts - his ties, and his socks in one drawer. Leslie would have the same in another and Owen in another, so they cou
ldn't complain, and there were always three of four shirts waiting. I was that sort you know, I - always - looked ahead. They looked after their own clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Coming round to meals in those early days of your married life, at Bute Road, where were meals eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In the dining room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Were there any occasions when they were taken in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No, not unless - perhaps - Saturday dinner hour we would have our dinner in the kitchen. That's to keep the dining room nice and clean you know for Sunday. That's the only time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Where would you do your cooking then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What sort of - what did you cook on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
On a coal stove first. But afterwards I had a gas stove, but I made - all my own bread and cakes you know, my children never knew the taste of bought food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well before the children of course went to school, that would be about - half past eight. Then they would come home to dinner you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What members of the family were present at breakfast time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
All of us, except Hal. He would get out at - he used to get out at half past five in the morning, because he had to walk to Mutley Plain, and catch a bus you see to Deveon port, it used to get in the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14175119\charrsid8333642 re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What time did he have to start work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I didn't exactly know but then he used - I think - well I don't know what time the - I believe it was about - I don't know whether it was seven or eight. Yes. Oh yes, well he worked all hours then that - during nigh
t time and day. In fact he worked too hard that - I had - I spent - I always said I spent - a fortune in - in medicines you see there was no welfare state in those days. And used to get the best that I could of the - chemists you know. Owbridges lung toni
c and every sort of thing that I could find.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did you usually have to eat and drink for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well the children usually had cereals. My husband had nothing. But a cup of tea. He never had any breakfast. And it's a strange thing, that my Leslie now - never has any breakfast. Isn't it funny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What would be your husband's first meal then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
He - I had to pack up sandwiches or sometimes I would make a little pie, and he'd -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 It would be his midday meal before he would eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 T
hat's right. But then I would cook him a hot meal - at teatime, you see when we had tea I would cook a hot meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the children come home for their midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Sometime - most - mostly. Mostly they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What would you normally have that meal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh every sort of thing dear. I know - during the depression - my eldest boy reminded me of it - during the war you know, he was sent abroad, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 enlisted}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  and - went abroad, and - he wasn't there very long but I remember I had a letter from him,
 and he said, don't worry about me mother, I am quite well, he said, do you know mum - what has kept us as we are? Your soups. I shall never forget the soups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you have anything special on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh always had a good roast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And anything different on Sundays for breakfast or tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, generally - well there was always sponges made up you know and - tarts of different kind and cream. Oh yes, they were well fed dear. In fact - my Leslie had diphtheria at the age of three and a hal
f and I didn't - don't think I had a doctor in the house for seventeen years. And that's saying something. If they had a sign of a cold - on would go the elderberries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
What did you tell me about the use of raspberry leaves, what ailment was that to help with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was to - to help in - birth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How did that help then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh - help, my dear, it's magical, that's all I can say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What actually was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well you see, I was married - in 1909, in 1910 - I weighted seven stone. And I had 
my first baby. I had it under sedation, and that babe - because where could I - wait a minute - now that baby weighed ten and a half pounds. That left me - a helpless cripple. It did, that really - that - first baby's birth ruined my life really, because 
y
ou see the doctor never attended to me at all. And it was two years after - I had - my second baby, same doctor, same treatment. And in those days you see - people like - like my mother they knew nothing about the after effects of birth or anything, so I 
w
as never attended to. And it's a wonder how I got on like I did. But you see it was - what was I saying, the war broke out in 1914 and we came down to Devonport, well that was in - when I was - looking for lodgings, that I came - through Devonport Park an
d
 I - I think I told you didn't I about the old lady that asked me in and offered me rooms. And the first thing she said to me, are you taking raspberry leaves Mrs Mellor? Of course I roared with laughing. I said, raspberry leaves, what on earth are you ta
l
king about. And she said haven't you heard of them? I said, no. What good are they? Oh, she said, they're magical. In confinement. And that dear - she - she said she would take me of course we quite agreed to stay there, and after we'd got settled down - 
t
hat dear soul put on her hat and coat and went into the - herbalist into Devonport and brought home a pound of raspberry leaves. And she put on some and - stewed them you know and gave them to me, and all the time I was there I kept taking them. Until I f
e
lt it was time to go home to mother. You see, by that time I - that was - Leslie would be the third child you see, and - I couldn't stay in lodgings you see with the - well in fact I'd left my little son - was taken down to my mother when the war broke ou
t first because I had the - Philippa you see and I had to take her with me, I couldn't leave mother with two babies. So I think that was why I was such a long time in finding lodgings you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How long did you take the raspberry leave then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Too
k them right on. Until the - until the babe - the - the hour the baby was born, and I shall never forget it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did that help with the confinement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh - my word. I rem - it was about twelve o'clock at night, and I said - of course mind - I wasn't f
ool - I said to my husband before - I'm not having a doctor in this house. Not for this confinement. Well you can imagine him. I wouldn't like to - I wouldn't like to tell you what he said to me. Anyway, he insisted I should. He - I said, you're not to br
i
ng a doctor here I tell you. He said, well I shall get the policeman - to bring a doctor. I said, all right, I'll be waiting for you. So he said, what are you going to do? I said, I'm going to fill up my kettle with boiling water. Now our - bedroom had a 
l
arge bay window, and a small window which looked right over the steps, you know. So I said, I'm going to boil a kettle of boiling wat - boil a kettle of water, and when you knock - and I'm going to bolt the door and lock it. And when you and your policema
n
 come I said, up comes the window and down goes the boiling water, you are - on you. I said, I think that'll finish your policeman. Which it did you know, he - he never attempted, so anyway when it - when the time came - of course I wasn't fool enough to 
a
llow myself to think that I could do everything myself. I engaged a real - good midwife you know, and I also had a woman in the house to take care of the children. See. And - I said to this woman - when I - the pains started, I said to her, here Broom, go
 
down and boil up a - good lot of raspberry leaves. What, hot as you can quickly. And Hal went off to get Mrs Harris. She didn't live very far away so you may depend he went very fast. But anyway - I drank some of these raspberry leaves. And Mrs Harris cam
e
 to the door. And when she got the bottom of the stairs she shouted up, oh Mrs Mellor, don't do that dear. She said, don't you urge, she said, you're going to hurt yourself. And I remember saying to her quite distinctly, oh by golly, I can't stand this pa
i
n very long. Now be - so - before she got in our bedroom that baby was in the world. Now that was raspberry leaves. Now - and then when I - that was the - that was - that was the - yes, that's - with the next confinement you see I did - the nurse came and
 
- I told you she cried bitterly, she said she couldn't stand seeing me - you know, attended by this doctor so I told her she needn't worry, so as I take - I told her about the raspberry leaves and of course - we did mind - I took - quite a bit but anyway 
w
e - the birth came all right. Oh it - it is marvellous. I - I - you see, people ought to know about these things. I tell everyone that I come across about them you know, perhaps they think I'm silly. But I do because I think if you know of anything - that
 helps anyone in any way no matter what it is, I think it's our duty to do so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
In those early days at home you made all your bread and cake and so on, did you bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes. One year I remember making one hundred and twe
nty pound of jam. Now. We went out, Ada and I, went - I - we had a - I had you know, they used to have large market baskets. And we went out to a place called Austin Forts, well you couldn't get in the fort, there was very high walls, but I was never daun
t
ed dear with anything. How I got up there I do not know. But somehow I got up the wall, and - whether I helped Ada up with any, I don't know, we both got in anyway, and inside the fort there was a veritable paradise of blackberries. Oh - ooh, we filled ou
r baskets full. And I came -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Who was Ada?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Pardon? She was my friends, she lived door - two doors up, she was a Cornish woman, and we were like sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This was in the early years of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, the - that's when the children were bigger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
In those early years when the children were small did you grow any vegetables or fruit? Did you have a garden there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Let's see. We did have the garden, I - told you before that we had the garden between us, when we lived in number twe
nty-one, that's when we took over - part of the garden, where we - we - we grew all our own vegetables, everything. And I even kept fowls. It's remarkable. I said to Ada one day, we said I think I shall - I shall have some chicken. She said, what - how ar
e
 we going to arrange chicken Kitty, we can't, we've got now here to put them. Well right down below our house in Alexander Road - there was a big - biscuit factory, I think they were called Wedgewood. Anyway, they had large cases selling. That some sort o
f
 - you know - big packing cases selling, they were big as that table nearly there, and they were sold then at one shilling each, and the timber was a quarter of an inch thick. Well on hearing of this - I said to my Ron - we had a vegetable boy that came a
r
ound with a - barrow, I said, you ask him - if he'll come on Saturday morning and go down to Wedge - there - I think it's Wedgewood they were called, and get one of these cases. Well he did so. And - we had several of them. And my husband and Ronnie helpe
d
 and they made a little store, first - and then they built a fowls house. Yes, under - under my - under my directions of course. And I went - up to - Ada and I went up to Mount Gold where you could buy day old chickens, and I remember that I came home - a
n
d I did - made myself a little - foster mother. Because I used to have my groceries sent up by the Co-op in beautiful wooden boxes, and I contrived a little foster mother, I made - showed Hal how to make it you know, cut the bottoms of the box - bottoms o
f
 the boxes in sections, put it on four legs, see, mount the box on that and I filled that with hay, and had a hot water bottle in under, went off and got my day old chicks and put them there. Had twelve and I never lost one. And from those twelve, I devel
oped - when we left Plymouth I had about twenty-five.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
That was later, but - that's why - how I started. So we always had - well of course it took a while you know before they started laying, but when they lay the eggs, we were never short of eggs you see, there were many days that I used a dozen a day.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you keep any other livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, nothing but - oh two cats of course, we always had cats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In those early days when the children were small in the first world wa
r how many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Not - not many times. Because you see - in the first world war we were rationed. And you could only have so much. But then of course I had to put my mind to work - as how best to maintain my family. I had onl
y thirty-eight and sixpence a week you see to spend, and that was to feed and clothe six. Now how many people these days could manage, would think of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 It was difficult to get food then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes. You see, we were only allowed a very little - amount of beef, and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was there any tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No, not at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Was it possible to get any extra meat from poaching like rabbits or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever have to go short so your husband an children could have enough?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Never. Because I - I did - my daughter - bought me a dog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This is in the early days of your marriage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
In the early days, yes. Yes, but - oh yes, well anyway, in the early days, like I say, we didn't know what to do, we ha
d this very - this light amount of - beef, well my parents you know living down here, they were good as gold, they used to send me now and then a huge boxful of food up, I have been sent a - a leg of pork and a - chicken, you know, at - various times, but
 
of course yes, but of course not every week you know. But anyway, way I remember - I went to the butcher one day and I said, Mr Bury, can I have some bones? He said, of course. So I said - well - I - he said, how much do you want? I said, I want as much a
s
 you can spare. He said, you know people here, he said, they wouldn't think of asking for a bone. So my word I had my market basket full, basket with me, and he filled up that basket, and I said, how much is it Mr Burley? He said, one shilling. Now, in th
o
se days - he - they did not cut the meat off the bones, not like today, they scrape them as bare as possible. But - I used to go - I went home with this big basket, I could hardly carry it home. Went out in the kitchen and laid them all out, I cut off eve
r
y bit of meat that I could find - first. And that meat - I'll bet you out of that basket full of bones I would have had - at least two pound of beef, you wouldn't believe it you know, well then - I took the bones, and I had two roasting tins and I would f
i
ll the roasting tins with the bones, roast every bit of fat out of them. Pour this fat into a quart basin. And by the time I'd finished roasting all my bones I had a quart basin of dripping. Well that didn't dispose of the bones. They were then - taken an
d
 put in a - I went and bought the largest saucepan I could find on Mutley Plain. And the bones were put in the - saucepan, and water put on and they were stewed all day. And allowed to remain. Well you know I could even take some fat off those bones then.
 
And then I made soup. And we had every vegetable there was known, there was lentils, carrots, parsnip, turnip, everything except cabbage. You see if you put cabbage in a thing and let it stay you see it turns sour. So I never used cabbage, but all the res
t
 I made I put in. Well then with the beef that I had - I used to make a suet pastry, and I used to make a long pasty. And I made a cloth bag really to put this pasty in with strings at the end so I could lift it out, and I used to put all my vegetables in
 
the saucepan, and then - I used to make a beef pasty. With suet pastry, and put on top of the soup. And they each had a bowl, I've got some of the bowls here now I can show you, big ones, that they had their soup in, and then this pasty was taken out and 
cut into portions, so they all had a bit of meat every day. With - in one day or a - in one form or another you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did your husband need to have larger helpings of food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh no, he was a very small eater.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 The children would you allowed them to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Could they choose what they wanted to eat or did they have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
They never - no, they were never allowed to choose, as a meal was put on the table - so they ate it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How would you feel if they left food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 They never did dear. That was the trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Could they wait until things on the table were offered like the salt or would they ask for things to be passed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well if it was out of r
each of course they would ask, but if it was in - within reach they took it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 They asked for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, many times you know - there are many times when I've gone without any dinner at all without them knowing it you know, because t
hey used to say, is there any more mummy? And I would take their little plate you know and - my dinner was always put back in the oven. While I was serving them. And I would take part of my dinner, and they didn't know. My husband didn't know. I did that 
- - done that many times. During the depression.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Would you allow them to bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Not - not at mealtimes, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When did the members of the family leave the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When the meal was finished, we never had any y
ou know jumping up and down or anything like that, there would - they sat down until we all finished and - then it was natural enough for the children you know to clear the table and - wash the dishes without any asking. You see, my husband was a very str
i
ct disciplinarian, and I think I had to do - only in a different way from what he did. Would carry out his orders as far as behaviour or anything was concerned you see. So - he would set the standard and I had to keep to it, you see. But I did mine in a l
oving way, but still I had obedience.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Did the children have to hold their knives and forks in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes. Oh yes, they were always taught to behave correctly at table.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they ever bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Not during mealtime, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did all the family present for the meal sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they have their own regular places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I did. Mostly. On Sunday - Satur - on S
undays - Hal always carved the joint I was never a carver. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
How did you manage feeding and seating the children when they were too young to feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh well I - they were all - the baby was always in a high chair you see so - I used to feed them then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Remember when they started to join the family in meals, about what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well it - in fact when they were tiny - when we were having our meals, the high stool was always brought close to the table, so that the baby was always like at one with the family you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
When the children were young did you feel there was a right way and a wrong way of bringing them up?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
I did. I didn't realize it at first. But when my second child came - I became aware - of the terrible respo
nsibility that lay on my shoulders, you know, I shall never forget it. And - I wouldn't say that - I was converted or anything like that, I just made up my mind to be - good, you know, I was brought - brought up by a Christian mother, but then I made up m
y mind that I had to - have help. So inwardly I asked for it and I got it. And that's how I've got on ever since, I've never doubted but what I've - been taken care of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You prayed about it did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you and your husband have the 
same ideas about bringing up the children or different ideas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh no, we were about the same, you know, he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you talk about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well we - well we were very much of a mind you know. We were both interested in - in most things in fact i
n politics in history. Well - all - every - in everyday occurrences we always had something to discuss you know because - he would always come home with some news of something that had happened in the yard and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was there anyone else you used to talk 
to if you were worried about the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, well if I was - I had this friend - that lived two - just - two doors up. Now we were more than sisters. We were really. We used to - always go shopping together. And she had two children - that were
 the - just exactly the same age as - as my Owen and my Leslie and she had - Roy and - Rosamund. So that - we were always together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever consult your mother about the children when they were small?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, I couldn't you see, she was home he
re so - I had to depend entirely on my own - on my own self.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You didn't see mother very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No. Especially you know during the wars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you and she have the same ideas about bringing up children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, mother - mother was very strict. She never told us twice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever were you ever in touch with your mother-in-law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I - I saw my mother-in-law once, and that was before I was married, my husband took me up to Manchester to introduce me to his family. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What family did he have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh - his mother had eleven children. Yes. And it's a strange thing, she was left a widow with eleven children, but she brought up every one of those children - that from the age of eight - they had to do something
. I can remember my husband saying - that at that age - he took breakfasts - to the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 mills}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  - for so many people, he had a round ring you know - and - the - cans of tea or something, he used to hang around this ring and before he went to school he went to 
the - mill you know, with the - their breakfast then I suppose they would have a bit of something before they left because they - started work very early in the mills then you know, and Hal - used to carry their breakfast meals. Well then - he was - be pa
id about a shilling a week something like that you see, well then - everyone had to do something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
He was brought up to be engineer, how did they manage, did he win scholarships or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well, he went to a grammar school, I know that he was educat
ed, you know, when he got any age, I don't know exactly - what - whether he went for a exam or anything but he was educated - at a grammar school, and then when he left school he went in - he studied at engineering - firm you know, for several years, and 
then he got to Brunner Mond and Company, that was the Steel Corporation at Stockton-on-Tees, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Did his mother have to bring the children up on her own or did her husband live for a little while?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Her husband died when he was forty-four. Leavin
g her with - these eleven children, and the - youngest one was two years of age. But shortly after her husband died this baby died, the last baby died. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 So you only met her the once then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Pardon? I only saw her - only saw her the once. She w
as in bed then, an invalid. She'd been in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Where was your husband in the family, was he the youngest or the eldest?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh there was - the eldest was - Sally. Sally and then - oh what was the - I forget names - so - he was called Herbert.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 She had three daughters and seven sons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. All - to bring up. And she brought them up - in a manner that - well that - you know, she had strict obedience though she was in - they just worshipped their mother I think, and her will was law. She was a ve
ry good woman I should say. And - they went to her for - you know, always consulting mother about everything I think. They were a very - closely knit family, very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the girls go to work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In the - in the mills.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the others have apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. Yes. They were all - well - Luther, he - he went in - the - in the clerical line. They all did well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
To come back to your own children, can you tell me some of the thing you felt you ought to do for them, how about affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh I never - I never held back affection. Do you know, the - my - my youngest son - if he forgot to kiss me - before he went down the hill, when he was quite a way down, he would come back again. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Were you never worried about their safety?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. Because they were always taught - to walk on the pavement. And never to cross the street - without looking - where they were going. I was very particular about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. District.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you want them to share their worries with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. Well we were - we were more - than - we were more like a - well, my husband used to say to me you're as young as they are. And I remember someone coming in one day and I was playing games with them and they said, which is the ol
dest of you lot? Oh I was one with the children you know, I stud - I studied their interests from - from every point of view.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How did you want them to behave towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well it - well - behave, well they behaved as I - I don't know about othe
r peoples children but - you know, they would never hardly go out of the house, if they were going out for anything - always kiss me. Always. Goodbye mum, and always had a kiss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When they were young did you and your husband ever manage to go out on yo
ur own together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Not very often. If there were any political meetings of course - I loved political meetings, I remember - I've heard all - oh - Mr Shinwell, George Lansbury, I can't remember all the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 names}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  that I - we've gone to political meetings but I've heard so many of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
This political meeting you told me about when you were a young woman, when these lads came in displaying articles on poles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What happened after that, did the meeting break up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes, well of cours
e every body roared with laughing, it had to break up you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No discipline on talking after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No, they might as well - no, that stopped the meeting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 If you were able to go out together who looked after the children then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Wel
l we never - we never went out without - we never went out very much at all we used to go to choir practice and Hal always attended his AEU meeting as he called it. He was the secretary for the AEU - department you know. Yes, and he used to go to a - an o
ffice out to Mile House, that was quite a way from our house, used to go out there to the meetings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did he take any active part in politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, not out - he would go canvassing you know. They were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 For which party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh the - Socialist party. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In Plymouth?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. We - we took our - well we took our stand - from a christian point of view. Because you see - we had seen so much - of poverty. And wealth. Because during our - as I say the first few years - the first year o
r two of my married life, I went with him - and he said one day, I'm going to show you Kitty, what a slum is like. And he took me to one of the big cities we were in and showed me a slum. And I remember I came home - and I laid my head on the table and I 
cried as if my heart would break.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you remember where this was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
At Stockon-on-Tees. And - he happened to have - a sister there as - a sister-in-law there staying at the same time, Luther's wife, and I know she said to me, it's no use crying Kit
ty dear, you cannot help it. I can remember that - I shall never forget that, that was my first - introduction to what a slum was I think - I think you know that's what made - me a Socialist you know, because the difference was so great. That you wouldn't
 believe it unless you saw it. You wouldn't really. You can - you cannot imagine - they used to have a toilet for about two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 dozen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  houses. One toilet. You see, you - we can't imagine it. People that have been decently brought up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did the people look puny and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 hungry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh they did. In their - in the slum places they did and the children. I can remember seeing little dears in a - in a wooden box, you know, sitting down - I suppose their bigger brothers were out playing around and this baby would be put
 in a wooden box, you know, and it - they did look awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 A kind of a make shift playpen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you see any of them barefoot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh well the - they were nearly all barefoot. That was the - of course, in the summertime they were - would be barefoot. Well you see what the wages were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you remember you or your husband voting before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you remember your husband voting before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well I think he first election we voted for were when - when we - got a
 home in Plymouth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 There was one in 1911 and one in 1918 I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I don't expect we voted in 1911, I can't tell you, but I know that - we voted always after - after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you or your husband feel that under any pressure from anybody to
 vote for any particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh no, we had decided opinions. And we never changed, and no matter who, if a - if a - officer - you know, if a member of the op - opposite party you know came to my door, I would never argue. You see, because there's no use in arguing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Were you or your husband a member of the Socialist party, or just a supporter?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Just a supporter. Well Hall would go around canvassing for them, you know, carried the - if they wanted anybody to take around leaflets or anything like that but - he was never what you call an active member.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you take any part other than at election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No, only telling - people why I - why I took the stand I did, you know. You see, I had seen such dreadful things - in Russia too, that influenced my lot a light. Oh an awful lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 When you and your husband were not working how did you spend your spare time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Out in the garden. You see - our garden - well you know we've got that - you see that field in the front of the house, well our garden was nearly as big as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was summertime, what about winter, did you ever go out of an evening?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. No, not - in the summer - on - in the summertime we used to go across to across to Corsand and - that little island now is 
made in - well you - I think it's made into a bird sanctuary, I forget what the little island is called, we used to go by steamer across to Millbrook. And spend the day there, yes, oh yes, we - we used to have little outings like that you know, and then -
 
there were - oh we were - Ada and I, and the children, well all of us, Mr Peters - I can remember on a Saturday, when the children were small - we used to take a kettle and - and a teapot - and you ought to see us laden up, I had a pushchair you know, bec
a
use of - the youngest baby was - not - able to walk say about two or two and a half well then - I would push so far, and - Mrs Peters would carry her - say Roy, well then - Hal would - then - whoever was was in the pushchair would be taken and Hal would c
arry that when and then Rosaumund you know, we took it in turns, they all shared - the pushchair, and we used to go to a place - right outside, what's it called now - it's - it was open to the public, but the public - it's on the - Lord - oh on the - now 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 isn't}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
 it funny the name right opposite - Lord - begin with an S - estate. Isn't that a strange thing, place with the same - said it thousands of times. But any -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You used to go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 We - with this - this - little place belonged to them. Well th
e public you see like they are, they will abuse everything, and we used to go off in the mornings, and we would take our kettle and our tea, and then we would pick sticks, you know, build a fire, boil our own water, and we had - a thing of cream and every
t
hing with us - everything with us you know, and we - we did - did not cut up sandwiches and take with us, we took a loaf of bread and took the butter and everything - and made our sandwiches there because I think sandwiches always goes dry. So that was on
e thing we always did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did either of you go to any clubs, institutes or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. I've never entered a pub in my life. And I don't think our - I don't think Hal has. We were strict }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 teetotallers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  then, I can remember this - I must tell you this - the - keeper of the forest, had a golden wedding anniversary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This was in Russia?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
In Russia. And all the members - of the English people there were invited, so there was about - if - we - they had a huge house, there were about fifty of us there.
 And - we had - oh - they - used to roast turkeys, you can tell what people - what extravagance people with money had, all the - those people - had legs - of turkeys. The rest of the - body was put back, do you understand that Everybody had a leg of turke
y.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What would happen to the rest of the bodies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Sent up for the servants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I suppose so. And - and - of course I couldn't speak Russian, I - I wish I had learnt the language, but I could speak a word - and I knew
 what was you know yes and no and thank you and different little things. But anyway - after the dinner - and dessert, champagne was brought around. Well we were strict }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 teetotallers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 . And - of course when you - see we rose from the table, you don't - didn't 
drink - when - after the dinner was over you had your glass of champagne, you were allowed to stroll around the room. A very large room, and they had lot - groups of farms and - different plants see, So Hal said, what shall we do with this Kitty. I said w
ell lets take a walk. So we pretended to put it to our lips really, and then we poured it on the plants, I've often thought what happened to those - to those plants. But we never did never tasted any kind of spirit - at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did Mr Mellor belong to any institute?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Not - he - well there was - the engineering, there's something he used to go once a month engine - in his - AEU activities. That was all. Oh, and we always went choir practice of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How often was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Sometimes - always 
once a week and sometimes twice, it all depended what they were giving you know, you - because they had a beautiful choir there, we were both in the choir - Mutley Methodist chapel, and we used to give the - Messiah you see right through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Who would stay with the children then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh that's when the children were older. But then - well like I say when the children were young you see I had this young cousin - and I had elder cousins of mother's, I always had somebody to call on. So that I knew - mostl
y while during the childrens - younger years I - I mostly had someone staying with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. Yes, the Co-op. And - they - they had a lady you know she came round weekly for the sub - subscriptions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Was th
at just saving or was it for a special purpose like for boots or sickness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No, that was for savings. You see, because you had your division - the purchases you made, but this was different, this was savings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did either you or your husband take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. No, he was - mind, he loved football. But although we lived in Plymouth all those years he never attended a football match.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you go walking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, we did, had lots of long walks together. And with the children - 
when when they were able you know to - when in fact like I say, Ada and I and all the children, we spent many days in the country.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did either you or your husband bet on anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 Plymouth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  did you go to any theatres or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. I think I'd been to the Theatre Royal once. And that was all. Mind, I always said - I always attended all the political meetings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Any cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Pardon? Yes, there was a little - cinema - led - which led off from Belgrave Road as - well it was on Belgrave Road, and I used to go there sometimes in the afternoon you know, but I don't - when I felt I'd done up my work and - if there was a certain fil
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14175119\charrsid8333642 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  that I wanted to see I used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you have any pets in those early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Ye
s, always had two cats. Because my children, they were terrors, they - if I would have allowed them you know I should - have a zoo. They were always so fond of animals. In fact we came down here with two black cats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you have any friends other than
 your friend Ada that you would visit or come to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, oh yes, we had a - Mrs and Mr Martin, and - the - the others - the - there was another couple, but those two couples - they used to come regularly like - now - Mr and Mrs Martin, that's
 Fred - Fred and Edna, they would come once a month. We would go out - say we'd - one - Saturday we would go out their place to tea. Dinner - you know, go }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 
after dinner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  and stay to tea and spend the evening, and the next Saturday you know we used to take it in turns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you always share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, always. And we kept them you know all the time until they - until they left Plymouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Would they come in to tea or to a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh - oh yes, any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No particular days or occasions that they would come?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well they usually - they would usually say to Hal the day before, you know, tell Kitty to expect us tomorrow, we'll be out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they ever call in casually without invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, if they were about. But we lived - right on the very }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 edge of Plymouth. Opposite the C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 achewater.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Away from your friends a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. And they lived out to Devonport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what would you do when you and your friends got together, your friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well we would play - we used to play cards a lot you know. We had any amount of - scores of games of cards, we - well - we were often playing whist with the children got better - bigger - you k
now, older they could - they would join in but we - had our friends - we - they'd always have a game of whist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What about music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh and singing. That was a - that was a well known thing, that was expected you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Your first home was rented, how did you feel about your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Never saw the landlord - never saw the landlord - at all but once. It was funny. I did go across when - when my husband came and said he had a house. And I got the address of the - owner, I did go across and t
hat was a long way off. It was over - oh - what part of that would be - lets see - near Oreston I think, it was a long way off I know I went to see the - the landlady it was a landlady at first. I went to see her and made myself known you know, and then o
f course we used to send the - money by - you know, by - cheque. Or - if they were - anybody was around - you know, they would call, but it was mostly sent by cheque.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In the district where you lived at Plymouth, who were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14223879\charrsid8333642 considered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642  the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I don't know that anybody was considered the most important. There was - there was members of the council who lived there, you - had - positions on the council, but - you know, we never thought they were - more important than we were real
ly, they were nice people. Everybody round us was very nice. In fact I don't think I used to pass anybody without they used to say good morning or good afternoon.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What about the shopkeepers, who would they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well that I can't tell
. But I do know - Sir Richard Winnicott I know him and his family, they always attended - Mutley Wesleayan chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What was his business or way of life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well - they had a - they had a bit - now they - I don't know what business they were in but 
they had a big business in the Octagon. There's a place in Plymouth called the Octa - Octagon you know, and it's a - row of like - business firms around, I know they had a business there. I think it was more like a general business of a - of - well - furn
iture and - play - you know - well - paints and all - paper and all sort - you - sort of household - things. Not a - not an established furniture shop but - you know, sort of everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 The Octagon is a shopping area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh that was a - really was 
- I suppose it must have been in a - eight sided place you see because - there were business houses all around. It was known as a business quarter, the Octagon was, I daresay - I don't know anything about it now you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This Sir Richard Winnicott, w
ho would he mix with socially? Teachers or other employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well I suppose, yes, they were very friendly people. I know it was through Sir Richard Winnicott really that - Leslie got in the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was later of course, I mean in the ear
ly days, what about teachers, were there any teachers in your locality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh well they - they would mix with - just you know - I think there were two schoolteachers well - naturally enough, like mixes with like, you know what I mean. Everybody was very
 friendly, though I've never - in the thirty-three and a half years - I lived there - I only went in one person's house once. And she asked to see me, sent up by one of the children asked to see me about something, and I know I went down to see her, but -
 I was never one for visiting, except our - own friends, and like you say all our friends were through Hal working in the dockyard you see and making friends, and they lived out to Deveonport, or out to Pemble which was quite a way from our home. Be -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
What sort of people would you say went to church, was there any difference in church and chapel in Devonport?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No I shouldn't say so. We had a - we had all - all the heads I should think of the businesses almost in - in - you know, in our chapel that
 anybody could have, all the heads of - the big shops. But several, like I say now, Pophams they would be - Popham's and Dingles, they would - they were church people. But - like I say, we had a lot of business people - builders and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Were there any landed gentry around there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well I was telling you about this estate. It was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or were there different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I think they all - well - I couldn't t
ell you about the poorer - you know, anybody in what we would call the poorer classes lived, I think they lived more from hand to mouth - you know that anything else, funny, it - I think a lot of people are like that today you know, they don't look forwar
d - to tomorrow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you think that any one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, I - I do think that. I do think that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Can you remember anybody -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Do you know, that my Philippa was - do you know, my Philipa was the first girl 
to enter Plymouth High School form a - through - for a scholarship, and my Ron was the first boy at Devonport High School. And - they were looked down on, there's no doubt about that. My - my son would have been much better off if he - been of a - differe
nt - political persuasion, I'm quite certain because he went by the name - they nicknamed him Lenin. That's true, in Devonport High School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What about Philippa then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
And - Plymouth High School, at first she was treated badly. You know, they would
 - oh say nasty things behind - you know, ay the - not for her to hear, but she was the sort of girl you know, she had a very independent spirit, and she would never quarrel with 'em or - she just ignored them. And I - now I'll tell you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you remember if there was any distinction between craftsmen and labourers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, there was. There was a great difference between craftsmen and labourers. There was a - in those days there was a distinct - you know, there was a distinction between - certain classes, there's no doubt about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you have a struggle to make ends meet at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well, during - during the depression I did - I had an awful time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In those years before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you know anyone ther
e who had to get help from the Guardians or from the Parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No. No. I didn't - you see - I had no - what I call real friends except these - one or two that we kept to you know and they were - all pretty well well - pretty well off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What differe
nce did it make to you if your husband was ill or out of work, was he ever ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh he was ill several times. But it didn't make any difference to me, I waited on him, you know. And of course we had doctor but no welfare state in those 
days but - he would go to work, my husband I think would go to work as long as he could stand on his two feet. I saw him go out the house one day - and I - I was worried and he'd been home for a couple of days, and - I didn't want him to go to work but he
 
went out you know and he went flying on the pavement. But he insisted on getting up and going to the dockyard, he thought the dockyard couldn't get on without him you know. Like I told him, you needn't worry dear, the - dockyard will go on just as well an
d
 it isn't going to stop. But I think - he's like mu Leslie. Now in all this land there isn't more conscientious - person than Leslie. That boy has killed himself really. He's lame now, and he's undergone some very - very - bad operations too, very bad, yo
u see he had the artery taken out from under his right leg, well that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 To go back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 The birthdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
The children at home in the early days, if they had a birthday would that be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes. There was always a bi
rthday cake made, always, oh yes. I always made special fuss of them at - anytime like that you know. Well I - I've always said I haven't lived really. I've been you know - I've been so much - part - the - well they were my life you know. I existed just f
or my family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they have guests to tea on their birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh yes, oh yes, they always had a - few friends in to tea. And what -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they have presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, yes, always presents from granny and aunties. Oh they were never forgotten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Can you remember anything you did with your husband and the children on Christmas day in those early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well we nearly always came home here for Christmas. Nearly always came home for Christmas. And there was one time that we were always together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 On the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes. Well we were a very closely knit family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you remember anything you did on Christmas Day then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh just playing games and a lot of singing of course of - Merrits carols, I got - I think I've even got them in - on my piano now. I pick them out of the cupboard you know, thinking - I'll get them ready for Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you play any Christmas games with the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes. I was - like I say, I've been asked - many times, who is the oldest of - of - of this party, them or you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did your husband join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
No, he was never a - he was never as lively as I am - as I was. I've always been a child at heart I think I still am. I think I'm really now undergoing my second childhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you read aloud to each other or to your children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I read a - I read to the children but Hal didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you belong to the library when you were in Plymouth in the early days?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I - every Saturday afternoon - and I lived a long way from the library
, 'cos we lived right on the very outskirts of Plymouth, and I used to - instead of getting on a - on - I - tram, I used to walk in - and ride home. Well I used to go to the public library - and I used to get six books. I got one for the very tiniest, the
 
smallest, right on, what I - would suit the ages, every Saturday of my life - I used to go to the library. Public library you know and get six books. Well then I would get on the tram then and go as far as I could you know, to get home, because there was 
such a lot to carry. But I made sure that they always had good books to read.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What about newspapers, did you have any newspapers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, yes, we always took, - well as long as we were able we - we - took different papers, we used 
to take the Independent. Then we took the Daily Herald always. And any other paper that came along, you know, those were the regular ones that we always did take. But if - if I went out you know and there was a Mirror or any other kind there and I thought
 there were any news on it that I - wanted to know I used to buy them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What about magazines, did you have any magazines in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, I was always - had plenty of magazines from - various friends. There were some of them that used to take
 up magazines you know and knowing I was fond of them they used to save them for me. Yes, well I took up - Woman's Own I used to take up Woman's Own, I had Woman's Own for many years. I had it up to - well I think all the - as far as I can remember until 
I came down her. I had Woman's Own - Own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you take the children out visiting friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, I didn't. Not very often, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you take them shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Never took them shopping. No, I never took them shopping. And - I ca
n remember going with my two tiny ones, you know I said - I told you I made all their own clothes. Well I'll show you one day a photograph, well - but I did - and I was very - particular in how they were dressed you know, and I - had the very best materia
l I could get - here I would go short of food for - to keep my children different from anybody else and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Can you remember anything you did on Bank Holidays with the children when they were small? Did you go away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, we mostly went out to these 
woods. The - Bur - no it isn't Burleigh - I would - Lord Saltram's Estate, that's it, Lord - Saltram House, well this is - this part was a part of a Lord Saltram's estate. We took our - took our kettle and our teapot, we took everything for the day, you o
ught to see us - loaded up. And there were no buses in those days you know we had to walk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, never had a holiday in my life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Except for coming here for Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Except for coming here for Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 At home with your husband and little children did you say grace at meals?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No we didn't. I don't know why, we didn't. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No. We had - but I always went to - went to - with my children to bed yo
u know, they always - knelt down with them - for them to say their prayers. That's until they got quite big, you know, until they got big enough to - do it for themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
You were saying that on Saturdays you usually did clean up the house for Sunday, was there anything different that the children did, did they have different clothes to wear or do anything different of a Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well, the Saturday they usually - had the - they usually used to go off say of playing cricket you know like a lot of schoolboys did. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 But when they were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh when they were little we usually - went off like I say then and - spent afternoon - perhaps out in the comptaon Park Fields, we wouldn't go very - any further than that, we would - even take our tea out there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
They went to Sunday school ten o'clock in the morning. After they went - and after they were about - I didn't send them - to Sunday school in the morning until they were past five, because I thought it was too much
, you know, you - and I never took them to chapel until they were - I don't think it's right to take little children to - to any place of worship when they don't understand the word, where they have to sit perfectly still. I don't think that's right. So I
 
never used to take them, but as soon as ever they got big enough of course I took them, but they used to go to - as soon as ever they passed their fifth year - they went to Sunday school - Sunday school at ten o'clock in the morning From Sunday school the
y went into chapel and remained through the big service. Came home to dinner. At half past two they were at Sunday school again, until four. They came home to tea, and at six o'clock they were at chapel again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did they put on different clothes for chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes. Oh yes. And like I say, if they went to town you see they had different clothes on. But as soon as the minute they came in doors they were taken off, you know, and changed to - to their second class - well I always kept their - you know,
 their clothes were always perfect and - well at least in my eyes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You wrote poems, can you remember any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh yes, I can remember lots of them, but I remember one that I wrote - about women, because I never heard women ever - you know - written a
bout at all. It's this. We are sailing on a voyage, across the sea of life. We meet with many storms we know, and tempests will be rife. But we must map our destiny, and we must have control of every chart, and mark each reef that wrecks the human soul. T
h
ey say the hand the cradle rocks is that which rules the world, if that is so upon our ship one flag we'll ne'er unfurl, and that's the flag of mammon, he sails on every sea and captures everything worthwhile. I pirate bold is he, but we shall fly the fla
g of love, is worth much more than gold. To guide us clear of every storm, it will our lives unfold. Through all the stress and strains of life we should see its golden ray, our lives will be a gladsome thing, when love alone holds away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You are Mr Wasley's only sister aren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Do you remember the time before the war when Mr Wasley lived in Camborne? Do you think he was in employment then, or do you think he had his business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well I think before the war broke out he was working 
at Holman's. He had a business before. But - during his dinner hours you know, the girls used to mind the business and I don't think they took much care of it and his business fell off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That - that must have been after th
e war. See the business fell off so he sold the business. And then he came - before the war, that - he - he was - had the business before the war I think. What did he do, he must - he - he worked Holman's I know. And I know that he had a business and I kn
ow that he had to sell it, because of - he had a wonderful start there you know but somehow it fell off. And it - well let's see, his daughters, they would be about sixteen and seventeen then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 They were born in 1909?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 1909. Well the - what would that - they would bring them to be what then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
At the end of the war, 1918, they would have been nine then? Do you remember much about your early days in Chacewater?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well - the one thing that I can remember - and it's as plain to me today as if i
t happened yesterday. I know that - we lived in a tiny cottage in the Fore Street down to Chacewater, because an aunt of mine had occupied this house and she was going to - the States, and we - when father got married they went - took this little cottage 
d
own to Chacewater. And it was a pouring wet day, and there was a little vestibule, and mother took a little stool which I have under my chair at the present moment, she put - Albin and I to sit on this little stool, to watch the rain pouring down, and the
r
e was a huge steam roller coming down. Now the particular thing that I noticed, and I wasn't eighteen months old, was the colour of the water that was gushing out from that roller. See the roads had been new laid, the farmers used to break up the stones, 
a
s you know, there used to be stone - crackers they called them, well they used to break them up and bring them down and these steam rollers used to - press them into the roads. Well you - then that used to bring up the water - the clay water, and the wate
r was red. Now I remember that and I can see that water now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How was the water red then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
From the clay. You see, with the pressure of the steam engine - steam going down, it was turning up the under soil you see, and the water was coming up red - well the - the colour of clay, see. I remember it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 From the tin mines would it be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. Because there were mines all around you see was Kellifreth was working, Illifreth was working, and Wheal Busy was working. There were mines all around then
. But when we were - before I was eighteen months old we came up here to the farm, to live in this little cottage where I am situated now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
You remember that little cottage down at Chacewater, do you remember anything about it, how many rooms there were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Two rooms, and a little kitchen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That would be one up and one down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
One up and one down, and a little kitchen behind. Now I do not remember - being brought up here, see the time in between - but I do remember that when I came up here - I can remember the clothes I wore. I was - must have been a vain little soul you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What were they like then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well one was a red velvet dress, I never forgot it you know, and another was a white dress - and an aunt of mine had embroidered it
 with yellow braid, they used to do braidwork on the - on - instead of embroidery they used to do braid work. Now I can remember those two dress - dresses the same as if I had them now. See, I - I think I must have been a very proud little soul, even in t
hose days. Well I had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What year were you born then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well I was born in 1884.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And you were about what age that you came up here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well before I was eighteen months old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And you can remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This address here, what's this called now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Jolly's Bottom Farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 This little cottage is a part of the farm buildings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
A part of the farm buildings, you see my cousin, she occupies the farm house, well then when - when - we left the cotta
ge, when my - aunt went to - America we came here to live. You see, and we stayed here for years. And my grandfather farmed the farm. Well when grandfather died - my father bought the farm. So he farmed it for several years, or mother farmed it, father wa
s away abroad you know, he served several years - he was in South America as an accountant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 A sort of mining accountant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, mine accountant for a big firm. He was an accountant, him and a parsons son, and the schoolmaster's son, I remember thei
r name, Albin Innes was the schoolmaster's son, and Fred Church was the parson's son. And those three, went to America together - South - South America they went, and I have a photograph of them here taken together, sent home from America, I've still save
d it up. I'm a very sentimental soul you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you remember your father well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh well, I should think I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 He was abroad quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
He was abroad and I remem - I was looking at my postcards the other day and I came across a pos
tcard from him, and he said, why haven't you written to me my darling, and I was only - I wasn't ten. But I used to write my father pretty regularly. I have been a great correspondent you know when I write a letter it's a newspaper. They all say that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How many rooms are in this cottage then that you moved into?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Four. And my aunt has had a - when we came - she added on another room to make a nice kitchen - and a modern bathroom where we have indoor toilets you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Is that when you came up with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
That's - no, that's - that's when - after the war. I could tell you - look - in - I was married in 1909. In 1910 my first son was born. After a most - terrific time, anyway - fortnight after my son was born - my husband had a commiss
ion to go to Russia. So he went off to Russia and I was left at home with mother. Well it took me a long time to get over that business, but - when my baby was four months old - I went to Truro and got a passport, and went off with my baby - alone to Russ
ia.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What year was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That would be in 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you stay in Russia long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 About a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 You were back here in 1911?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes. I suppose we were, but - I don't know exactly the dates. I think I - I - yes, I went to Russia -
 on the fifth of July 1910. When Ronnie was four - well Ronnies was about four months old, he was born on the thirty-first of March. And I went the - I think it was - March - April, May, June, July, that's right, I went on the fifth of July, to Russia.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How old was he when you came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Oh he was walk - oh he was walking. He was just - just over a year or - not much over a year old, I don't - I - I don't know exactly the date we came home. I can't tell you that, but we had to come home because t
he baby fell very ill, and I thought I should have lost him. And my hus - the - cold - affected my husband so badly - that he had to leave. And he - we came home. Well we hadn't been home very long - be - his company were a wonderful company, wo - they se
nt him first to a home at Udeltor in Devon to recover from his illness, and then they sent him to Jamaica, where he stayed for a whole year. To -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Did you go with him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 No, because I had two babies then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Which part of Russia was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Voznezsensky. The place was called. That was fifty mile from Moscow. So we the - I - I went into Moscow about twice. But we were in a - in a - proper country district you know. And - where Hal went - was ka cotton mill. And that cotton mill was bu
ilt by - Coates of England and a Baron Knoop, and it was built like a little city. It had four gates, east, west, north and south. And every gate - had an armed guard. And no one could enter that little city without a passport. That's how particular they 
were. But the British mind were allowed to go in and out when they liked, but none of - none of the Russian people weren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How did your husband get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Through - through his company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Which company was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 The Brunner Mond. They had the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Where were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Stockton-on-Tees. I bet - I bet their - I bet there's business there still, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 They're part of ICI now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Yes, they are, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 He was an engineer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Oh he was a very clever engineer. In f
act when we came home - I - of course there's all - there was two years - two years after I had my little daughter. Well she was born - a fortnight after my husband left for Jamaica, wasn't that funny. So he hadn't seen - Philippa until she was about a - 
a
 year old you see. So anyway - he made up his mind then that as he had two children, he wanted to - be with his family, and have a home. Well we - so he gave up his job at Burnner Mond - and of course he had no trouble in getting - a wonderful job at a pl
a
ce near Southampton. On - Totton we went - we lived, but I don't exactly - I think it was - I - I believe it was Lord Buleigh's estate, I don't know - some motor engineer he had a wonderful job there anyway, and war broke out while we were there. We just 
b
ought a new house - but before we could get into it, I know our house was - named St Agnes. And we were ready to go in and war broke out. My husband went to join the army. But as soon as the officials saw his credentials they said on no occasions Mr Mello
r
 could we let you leave this country. You're too valuable a man. So you must go to one of his Majesty's dockyard. Well of course seeing I was Cornish - he chose Devonport you see. So he left at once for Devonport. He took our little son down to - here, br
o
ught him down here to mother and I was left with the baby - to have the furniture stored, and then joined him at Devonport. And the time I had there my dear, walking the streets hour after hour, day after day, week after week, until I got so ill the docto
r said if I didn't stop - I should be in a very serious condition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Why were you walking the streets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Seeking for lodgings dear. And because I had that dear little baby by my side - people would open the door and when they saw her they would shut 
it in my face. There was only one place where a lady opened a door - and she said, I'm sorry my dear, I cannot take you. But, she said, I would love to take you. But she said, I took an oath that I would never have anyone in my house again. She said, last
 
Christmas - we had a couple here that had for - had a one little boy. And he had a carpenters set given him to play with, and they let that child cut the legs off her sideboard. See? So anyway - so anyway, we went - at last we found a place at Paisley Str
e
et. A lovely little flat. We were there a fortnight. My brother had found a home with his wife in Plymouth. So this Sunday - on the Saturday I sent out a word for them to come to tea with us on Sunday. They did so. And we had quite a nice time. On Monday 
m
orning - my sitting room door opened, and in came that landlady - she was called Mrs Nissen, she was a Jewess, she came in and you should have heard her, you would think I had done - made a criminal offence. She said, I've come to give you notice, she sai
d
, you've got to leave this place. So I said, for what reason? She said, you took this flat, she said, for yourself, and your husband, and you're not to have anyone else in here. So I said, well you get out of this room then. If no one else has any right i
n
, you have no right. I did. So anyway she said, I'll have you evicted. If you're not out of the house by the end of the week. So you can understand me - poor little soul feeling ill. And we were coming through - I tried lots of places and we were coming t
h
rough Devonport Dockyard, I always say that God has taken care of me, and we - after - when you get to the end of Devonport Dockyard there's Albert Road. And to lead down to Albert Road there's some steps. Well we were going down to this - these steps, an
d right as at the bottom of the steps there was a little what do you call it, al - not alcove, what do you call it where there's a few little - cottages? What do you call that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Terrace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 A - no, not a terrace, a little round place, what do you call those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Crescent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Cres - well like a little Crescent, it had six little - thatched cottages. Now we were walking down the steps - and I thought I should have fall dead - down - fallen dead faint. I said to my husband, I said, oh Hall, I must g
o somewhere and sit down, I said, I'm going off. I said, I'm going to one of these houses. He said, you can't do that my dear, he said, you can't go to a strangers house. But I was gone. And I knocked at the first door I came to. A dear old lady came out 
and she said, what is it my dear. I said, oh please, will you let me sit down. She took - put me on a chair and I fell off dead. So see what would have happened to me because - I was pregnant then with another baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How many children did you have altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 I had four children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And the first one was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 In 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That was your daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
That was - Ronald. Ronald was born in 1910. Phil - in March, march the thirty-first 1910. And Philippa was born in 1912, March the twenty-second.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Which was the next one then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well the next one wasn't born for three and a half years after, that was Leslie. Well of course between that you see a lot -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 1915?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 That's 1915. When - well you see - I told you didn't I, that we le
ft - we - in 1914 when the war broke out, he was sent to Devonport dockyard, well of course we were - I told you we went in - to this old - lady's cottage, well, I was - pregnant. And I stayed with her - until the - August. And then I came home to mother 
- and Leslie was born here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 And the youngest one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
And the youngest one, I thought I'd finished then. But the youngest one was born - fifteen months after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 1916 or 17?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well fifteen months after, let's see a minute. Owen was born - yes, 
1917 Owen was born. Well I finished then, we were living in Plymouth then you see, we'd got a house there then. Well we lived in Plymouth for thirty-three and a half years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did all your children do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well - all my children - passed thei
r scholarships for High School. And of course I regret to this day that we didn't have more money at the time but my Ronald - passed for Devonport High School, and he wanted to be an architect. He was a bril - he is a brilliant man. But - and he went thro
u
gh the exams, he paid three guineas for the first exam, five guineas for the second exam, when it came to the third exam it was ten guineas. So he came home and he said to his dad, he said, fath - dad, I've got to go for another exam but its ten pound. So
 
Hal said, that finishes it my son. There - these exams - you're learning theory - but you're not learning the business - of an architect. See? So he left Devonport High School, and came home. Well he didn't know what to do. But we were very lucky, my husb
a
nd and I were both in - Mutley Wesleyan Methodist Choir, and the Borough Surveyor, Mr Wibberley was the organist. See? So - my husband, we were talking it over one evening and he said I think I'll go up and see Mr Wibberley, see what he has to say. Well w
h
en he got up there he said the first thing I have to tell you Mr Mellor is - that before your son can become an architect he - you have to put down a sum of two hundred and fifty pounds. Well - Ron was seventeen and we had three younger than him. Well we 
d
idn't feel at that time you see that was during the first world war, we didn't feel we had the money to put down. But - I - I - and I was too proud - now look I could have had it from my parents, but we were too proud to ask for it, and I've regretted it 
t
o - it to - to this day, but Mr Webb - Weibberley - took Ron - and put him as an accountant - on the outside building, you know, in the council houses were building, he went around you see and took notice of - well took note of all the men's hours and the
 pace and everything, so that Ron - knew more about the - the drainage and sewage system than anyone in Plymouth. See?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 So he didn't become an architect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
So he - no, he didn't - he didn't become an architect because he hadn't qualified you see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did he become?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
He's the chief draughtsman. He's working there now. Well the second son - we didn't know what to do with him, he had no decided views on anything. But Ron did you know want to be an architect but Leslie had no decided views s
o we thought well, we'll have to think out something for him, where he'll have a good pension when he finishes. So we chose the Post Office. Well - Leslie had to stop his scholarship because you cannot enter the Post Office as messenger boy after you're f
i
fteen. Well he went in for the exam, and he topped England. This was - Leslie. He topped - he topped Britain. Well he carried that on, the wasn't very long before he went from one thing to another and he got a sort - he got to be sorter. And it was while 
-
 then he got to be - he was sent to Cornwall to visit - take - take over Cornwall and visit all the people in Cornwall that were connected - with the Post Office for there were - well there now I - I - I'm going before my time. There was a welfare - I thi
nk the Welfare Department you know was started in Plymouth. And there was an exam. Leslie put in for it, and he topped England. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did he become eventually then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well then he - he - you see, he had - he came to Cornwall, they gave him Corn
wall. So that he had to visit every postman - in Cornwall. Now I remember him coming down one day - a fellow had been washed off a rock, a postman. Well you see he came down - he arranged the funeral, he did everything for that poor soul, got her pension 
and everything, that was his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 He was a Post Office Welfare Officer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Yes, a Post - Post Office Welfare Officer. Well he stayed there, I can't tell you how long he stayed there. And - he came down one day, he used to come down you know for the 
weekend, and he came down one day, he said, mum, he said - I hear that - there's a post - the post being - advertised for a welfare - being made for a welfare officer in London. He said, I think I'll study a bit more and go in for it. Well he studied and 
of course he's now Chief Welfare Officer - for the Post Office for London, he topped Britain in that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did Philippa do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well Philippa - after she left school - she went to - went as - let me see. Oh, when she was seventeen - she went to Plym
outh High school you know. When she left Plymouth High School, the headmistress came home to me one day - over to me one day, and she said, Mrs Mellor, she said, I've come to ask you - if you will be willing for Philippa to go to Canada? So I said, what f
o
r? She said, well I have a niece in Canada, she's married a - a nephew to a millionaire, and they want a nice - English girl - that she could recommend thoroughly a lady, that would fulfil the position of nursery governess. So at seventeen mind you she we
n
t off to Playmouth - to Canada on her own, and got the job. So she stayed there two and a half years. Well they found her such a - thorough being - young lady, you know in every way, that when they went away for their holidays, they left the whole househo
ld, they had five servants, and three children. Well they would go off on their holiday, they left Phil in command. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 What did Owen do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Owen started in a warehouse, Ball and Company. And he rose to be commercial traveller.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 So they all got settled?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
So they all got good jobs you know. But Owen was - torpedoed twice during the war. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 But he came through?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
He came through, but after he came home - he went back to Ball again, but he was taken - Oh he had a dreadful illness, 
in fact - the company sent - for a specialist - from London to bring down a heart machine that had just been invented. And that was brought down and took up into Owen's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14175119\charrsid8333642 bedroom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 . And the doc - the specialist said on no account was I to be sent for. Because 
he was a commercial traveller you see and he spent all his - time with me, while he was doing Cornwall, and he must have been asking for his mother. So I didn't see him. But he did get - get over that. After a long time. And he went to work again. But I t
h
ink you know they sent him off to early. Because I - he said, yes, he said, he was - got in his car, and they had a slight incline - before they got in - he was living at - near Tamerton Foliat, before they got on a main road where all the buses were goin
g, and he'd got just to the top - was just getting on the road when he dropped - dead. And the car smashed right back in his house and smashed to pieces.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 How old was Owen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Forty-six. So during his - commercial time you see he stayed with me
 and he was a most affectionate boy any - any mother could have. I think that - well I don't know, he showed me such love that I - I missed him so very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 To go back to your own early childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Well my early child -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid808626 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11697723 PM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15288751\charrsid8333642 
Well let me see. Father would be about twenty-one I should say. Now I don't know how - I haven't got my father's birth, I - I - and I know when my mother died. But I don't know how old - I - I expect it would be in the family bible.
